posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked:
l use PathWeaver to draw a path and build it in the src/main/deploy . Then l use code to get it  , code is below:

Then l use the code to generate it

Above is part of my autonomous code , but when l simulate the whole code , it just quit . The error is below:

image 1434×732 73.4 KB

image 1434×732 73.4 KB

image 1434×732 73.4 KB

My whole code is here: 2021Swerve.zip (22.7 MB)

Can anybody help me with it?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: This was fixed in [wpimath] Fix IOException path in WPIMath JNI by lhvy · Pull Request #3485 · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub . Unfortunately, we haven’t made a new release since v2021.3.1 containing the fix. I’m not sure there’s a workaround either since the bug is in native code. Maybe downgrade?

link_counts.title: [wpimath] Fix IOException path in WPIMath JNI by lhvy · Pull Request #3485 · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: Where should l change , it seems that l have already use the java.io.IOException.

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: It’s not a bug in your code. It’s a bug in WPILib that’s unavoidable for what you’re trying to do (calling TrajectoryUtil.fromPathweaverJson() ).

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: So , is there any method to use Pathweaver’s path in an autonomous period?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: No, it’s completely broken until we do a release or you downgrade.

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: So, now , we can only use Translation2d to make some points and use this to complete the auto line?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: Yeah, making the trajectory in code instead is an option.

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: Will downgrade solve this bug? Why?

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: Is there any other solution? l think this is too difficult and complicated for a good auto code

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: Yes. The bug was introduced in [wpimath] Use JNI for trajectory serialization by prateekma · Pull Request #3257 · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub , which was merged after v2021.2.2. Downgrading to v2021.2.2 will fix the crash. It’ll just take longer to load the JSONs.

link_counts.title: [wpimath] Use JNI for trajectory serialization by prateekma · Pull Request #3257 · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: If l downgrade , will the extension be cleared?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: What extension?

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: vscode’s extension

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: Or can l install an older WPILIB’s extension from vscode?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: The old installer will provide a VS Code installation with the old extension installed already. Another option is manually editing the version string in build.gradle since that’s pretty much all you have to do to downgrade the robot project itself.

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: Will the latter option has a bad effect?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: You won’t have local copies of the maven dependencies, so the first time you build your code after changing the version, it’ll take a while downloading all of them from maven.

posts.name: Daniel Wenbo
posts.cooked: l just need to download the 2021.2.2 version and install it(let it cover the 2021.3.1 automatically)?

posts.name: Tyler Veness
posts.cooked: Yes, then change the version in your robot project. I guess you’ll have to download a bunch of stuff either way, so you might as well just make the one-line change in build.gradle and not bother with the installer.
